Resolved:
Kong 3.x's router rejected the route regex `~/api/users/(?!me$)[^/]+$` (meant to match /api/users/{id} without also matching /api/users/me) with "look-around, including look-ahead and look-behind, is not supported" — caught by `kong config parse`, not by reading the docs first, since nothing in Kong's plugin-facing documentation calls this out prominently. Fixed by switching every `{id}` path segment (users, products, orders) to an explicit UUID-shaped pattern (`[0-9a-fA-F]{8}-[0-9a-fA-F]{4}-...`) instead of a wildcard needing a negative lookahead to disambiguate from `/me`. This is also more correct on its own terms: Phase-1 fixes IDs as UUID strings project-wide, so the stricter pattern documents that contract instead of accepting anything.

The placeholder token used for the identity-service public key (`__IDENTITY_DEV_PUBLIC_KEY__`) appears twice in gateway/kong.decl.yaml — once inside an explanatory comment near the top of the file, once in the actual `rsa_public_key` field the render script is supposed to fill in. The first version of gateway/docker-entrypoint.sh matched the placeholder with an unanchored awk pattern, so it substituted the real key into the *comment* line (the first match in the file) and left the real field's placeholder line untouched, which meant `getline` had already hit EOF on the key file by the time awk reached the real occurrence — the field ended up empty, producing invalid YAML ("could not find expected ':'"). Only caught by actually rendering the file and running `kong config parse` against the output, not by reading the script. Fixed by anchoring the awk match to a line containing only the placeholder (`^[ \t]*__IDENTITY_DEV_PUBLIC_KEY__[ \t]*$`), which the comment line doesn't satisfy.

`kong docker-start`, the default CMD baked into the official `kong:3.9.3` image, is not a real subcommand of the `kong` CLI binary — running `kong docker-start` directly returns "No such command: docker-start". It only works because the image's own `/docker-entrypoint.sh` intercepts the arguments and translates them into the correct prepare-then-start sequence before ever calling the plain `kong` binary. Since gateway/docker-entrypoint.sh overrides the container's `entrypoint:` to do its own file-existence check first, it was calling `kong docker-start` directly and failing outright. Caught by actually starting the container and reading `docker logs`, not by inspection. Fixed by having the custom entrypoint `exec /docker-entrypoint.sh kong docker-start` once its own check/render step is done, instead of invoking the `kong` binary itself — this delegates the actual startup sequence back to the image's real entrypoint.

CORS preflight (OPTIONS) requests to every route came back 404 instead of a clean CORS response, because each route's declared `methods` list only had its real HTTP verb (GET/POST/PATCH/DELETE) and Kong's router won't match a route — and therefore won't run the CORS plugin's preflight handling — for a method the route never declared. Caught with a manual `curl -X OPTIONS` against the running container, not by reading the CORS plugin docs (which don't call out this interaction explicitly). Fixed by adding "OPTIONS" to every route's methods list. That fix immediately surfaced a second problem: once OPTIONS could reach a JWT-protected route, the jwt plugin's default `run_on_preflight: true` demanded a token on the preflight request too, which a real browser never sends on a preflight — every protected route's preflight would have failed closed. Fixed by setting `run_on_preflight: false` on the jwt plugin's config; verified afterwards that preflight OPTIONS returns a clean 200 with the CORS headers while a real unauthenticated GET to the same route still correctly returns 401.

All four of the above were caught by actually running `kong config parse` and a real `docker compose up` against this repo's gateway/kong.decl.yaml and gateway/docker-entrypoint.sh, then exercising the running container with curl — not by reading Kong's documentation and assuming it would work. The declarative config and entrypoint script in this repo reflect the fixed versions.
